Looking at the code, I can see that when a secondary axis inherits breaks from a discrete scale, it doesn't also inherit the names of those breaks as labels. Here's my proposed edit to fix this:

In the `init` method of the `AxisSecondary` ggproto object, after the section that handles inheriting breaks, add logic to also inherit the names as labels when dealing with discrete scales:

```r
init = function(self, scale) {
  if (self$empty()) {
    return()
  }
  transform <- self$trans
  if (!is.function(transform)) {
    cli::cli_abort("Transformation for secondary axes must be a function.")
  }
  if (is.derived(self$name) && !is.waiver(scale$name)) self$name <- scale$name
  if (is.derived(self$breaks)) self$breaks <- scale$breaks
  if (is.waiver(self$breaks)) {
    if (scale$is_discrete()) {
      self$breaks <- scale$get_breaks()
    } else {
      breaks <- scale$get_transformation()$breaks
      n_breaks <- scale$n.breaks
      if (!is.null(n_breaks) && "n" %in% fn_fmls_names(breaks)) {
        self$breaks <- function(x) breaks(x, n = n_breaks)
      } else {
        self$breaks <- breaks
      }
    }
  }

  # If labels are derived or waived, and we have discrete breaks with names, use those names
  if ((is.derived(self$labels) || is.waiver(self$labels)) && scale$is_discrete()) {
    scale_breaks <- if (is.waiver(self$breaks)) scale$get_breaks() else self$breaks
    if (!is.null(names(scale_breaks))) {
      self$labels <- names(scale_breaks)
    }
  }

  if (is.derived(self$labels)) self$labels <- scale$labels
  if (is.derived(self$guide)) self$guide <- scale$guide
},
```

The key changes are:
1. Added a check after the breaks handling to see if labels are `derived` or `waiver()`
2. For discrete scales, check if the breaks have names
3. If they do, use those names as the labels
4. This happens before the existing `is.derived(self$labels)` check, so explicit label derivation still works

This ensures that when discrete breaks have names (like `c(a = 1, b = 2, c = 3)`), those names will automatically be used as labels on the secondary axis, matching the expected behavior.

