content.text:
The error occurs because when you define `foo` in the `Child` class's public methods, R6 creates a locked binding for it. Then when the parent's `initialize` method tries to assign a function to `self[["foo"]]`, it conflicts with this locked binding.

Here are several ways to fix this:

## Solution 1: Use a different name for the dynamic method

```r
Parent <- R6::R6Class(
  "Parent",
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    initialize = function() {
      self[["foo_impl"]] <- function() {
        print('foo')
      }
    }
  )
)

Child <- R6::R6Class(
  "Child",
  inherit = Parent,
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    foo = function() {
      self$foo_impl()
    }
  )
)

child <- Child$new()
child$foo()  # Works!
```

## Solution 2: Define the method in private and expose it

```r
Parent <- R6::R6Class(
  "Parent",
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    initialize = function() {
      private$.foo <- function() {
        print('foo')
      }
    },
    foo = function() {
      private$.foo()
    }
  ),
  private = list(
    .foo = NULL
  )
)

Child <- R6::R6Class(
  "Child",
  inherit = Parent,
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    foo = function() {
      super$foo()
    }
  )
)

child <- Child$new()
child$foo()  # Works!
```

## Solution 3: Check if the method exists before assignment

```r
Parent <- R6::R6Class(
  "Parent",
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    initialize = function() {
      if (!"foo" %in% names(self)) {
        self[["foo"]] <- function() {
          print('foo')
        }
      }
    }
  )
)

Child <- R6::R6Class(
  "Child",
  inherit = Parent,
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    initialize = function() {
      # Don't call super$initialize() to avoid the conflict
      # Or implement your own foo logic here
    },
    foo = function() {
      print('foo from child')
    }
  )
)

child <- Child$new()
child$foo()  # Works!
```

## Solution 4: Use active bindings for more flexibility

```r
Parent <- R6::R6Class(
  "Parent",
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    initialize = function() {
      private$.foo_func <- function() {
        print('foo')
      }
    }
  ),
  private = list(
    .foo_func = NULL
  ),
  active = list(
    foo = function() {
      if (missing(.foo_func)) {
        return(private$.foo_func)
      }
    }
  )
)

Child <- R6::R6Class(
  "Child",
  inherit = Parent,
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    foo = function() {
      super$foo()
    }
  )
)

child <- Child$new()
child$foo()  # Works!
```

The cleanest solution is usually Solution 1 or 2, where you separate the dynamically created implementation from the public interface. This makes the inheritance pattern clearer and avoids naming conflicts.

